# Frequency table for categorical variables
# Vehicle Make
vehicle_make=as.data.frame(table(project_data$Make))

#try to keep the 10 categories with the highest frequency & categorize the rest as other
top10_vehicle_make= vehicle_make %>%
                   arrange(desc(Freq)) %>%     #Sort by frequency in descending order
                   slice_head(n = 10)               # Keep only the top 10 rows

#calculating the frequency count of the rest of the vehicle make
Freq_make11 = sum(vehicle_make$Freq) - sum(top10_vehicle_make$Freq)

#adding the "Other" last row to the vehicle mark
top_vehicle_make = bind_rows(top10_vehicle_make, 
                             data.frame(Var1 = "Other", Freq = Freq_make11))

#calculate the frequency percentage
top_vehicle_make$Freq_Percent = round(top_vehicle_make$Freq/sum(top_vehicle_make$Freq) * 100, 2)

avg_mpg_per_year <- aggregate(`Combined.MPG..FT1.` ~ Year, 
                              data = project_data, FUN = mean)
ggplot(avg_mpg_per_year, aes(x = Year, y = Combined.MPG..FT1.)) +
  geom_line() + geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Average Combined MPG Over Time", x = "Year", y = "Average Combined MPG") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(min(avg_mpg_per_year$Year), max(avg_mpg_per_year$Year), by = 3)) +
  scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 9, limits = c(17,26 )) +
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),  # Remove major grid lines
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank())  # Remove minor grid lines

#One-sample t-test (hypothesis testing) for Average Annual Fuel Cost of Tesla
t.test(project_data$Annual.Fuel.Cost..FT1.[project_data$Make == 'Tesla'], mu = 1971, 
       alternative = 'less')

#Two-sample t-test (hypothesis testing) for Mean Combined MPG by Vehicle Class
#get the dataset to be smaller 
vehicle_class1= project_data[, c("Year","Class", "City.MPG..FT1.", "Highway.MPG..FT1.",
                                "Combined.MPG..FT1.")]

#simplify the vehicle classes into "Compact", "SUV", and "Other"
vehicle_class1$class <- ifelse(vehicle_class1$Class %in% c("Compact Cars", 
                                                           "Subcompact Cars", 
                                                           "Minicompact Cars"), 
                               "Compact",
                        ifelse(vehicle_class1$Class %in% c("Sport Utility Vehicle - 2WD", 
                                                           "Sport Utility Vehicle - 4WD", 
                                                           "Small Sport Utility Vehicle 2WD", 
                                                           "Small Sport Utility Vehicle 4WD",
                                                           "Standard Sport Utility Vehicle 2WD", 
                                                           "Standard Sport Utility Vehicle 4WD"), 
                               "SUV", "Other"))


#filter class dataset to include only Compact and SUV classes
compact_vs_suv <- vehicle_class1 %>% filter(class %in% c("Compact", "SUV"))

#perform two-sample t-test on combined MPG between Compact and SUV classes
t.test(compact_vs_suv$Combined.MPG..FT1. ~ compact_vs_suv$class)

##  Welch Two Sample t-test

#Regression Analysis
#1. how annual fuel cost is affected by annual fuel consumption, combined MPG, and class

#simplify the vehicle classes into "Compact", "SUV", and "Other" like in the hypothesis testing
project_data$class <- ifelse(project_data$Class %in% c("Compact Cars", 
                                                           "Subcompact Cars", 
                                                           "Minicompact Cars"), 
                               "Compact",
                        ifelse(project_data$Class %in% c("Sport Utility Vehicle - 2WD", 
                                                            "Sport Utility Vehicle - 4WD", 
                                                            "Small Sport Utility Vehicle 2WD", 
                                                            "Small Sport Utility Vehicle 4WD",
                                                            "Standard Sport Utility Vehicle 2WD", 
                                                            "Standard Sport Utility Vehicle 4WD"),
                               "SUV", "Other"))
linear_regression = lm(Annual.Fuel.Cost..FT1. ~ Annual.Consumption.in.Barrels..FT1. + Combined.MPG..FT1.
                       + factor(class), data = project_data)
summary(linear_regression)

#2. predict Fuel economy score by Combined MPG, Annual Fuel Consumption in Barrels, Vehicle Class,
#Engine Displacement, Engine Cylinders, Drive Type 

#simplify the vehicle drive type into FWD, RWD, 4WD and AWD
library(dplyr)
project_data = project_data %>%
  mutate(drive_category = case_when(
    Drive == "Front-Wheel Drive" ~ "Front-Wheel Drive",
    Drive == "Rear-Wheel Drive" ~ "Rear-Wheel Drive",
    Drive %in% c("All-Wheel Drive", "4-Wheel or All-Wheel Drive") ~ "All-Wheel Drive",
    Drive %in% c("4-Wheel Drive", "Part-time 4-Wheel Drive") ~ "Four-Wheel Drive",
    TRUE ~ "Other")) # Includes 2-Wheel Drive and Missing Data

linear_regression2 = lm(Fuel.Economy.Score ~ Combined.MPG..FT1. + Annual.Consumption.in.Barrels..FT1.
                        + factor(class) + Engine.Displacement + Engine.Cylinders
                        + factor(drive_category), data = project_data)
summary(linear_regression2)
